    "text": "Yes — a modest, consistent one. Across 11 tagged sauna evenings versus 36 comparison days, your next-day recovery ran about 4 points higher — a medium-confidence link in your own data. The usual caution applies: sauna evenings are linked with better mornings, which isn't the same as causing them — those nights may also be your calmer, earlier-to-bed nights. Today happens to fit: your recovery score is 74%, a touch over your 7-day average recovery of 71%, and your HRV is 65 ms, above your 30-day average of 63.9 ms. Two ways to firm it up: keep tagging so the sample grows past 20 days, and hold sauna nights steady while training varies. If the gap holds across hard weeks too, that's about as close to a personal yes as this data gets.",
